  "response": "There is no direct scientific evidence that using computers causes the death of brain cells. However, prolonged computer use can potentially have some indirect effects on brain health:\n\n1. Sedentary behavior\n- Lack of physical activity\n- Potential negative impact on overall health\n\n2. Eye strain\n- Prolonged screen time can cause digital eye strain\n- May lead to temporary discomfort but not brain cell damage\n\n3. Sleep disruption\n- Blue light from screens can affect sleep patterns\n- Poor sleep can impact cognitive function\n\n4. Mental health\n- Excessive computer use might contribute to stress or addiction\n- Can potentially affect mental well-being\n\n5. Potential benefits\n- Computer use can stimulate cognitive functions\n- Learning new skills, problem-solving, and mental engagement\n\nRecommendations:\n- Take regular breaks\n- Practice good posture\n- Limit screen time\n- Maintain a balanced lifestyle\n- Use blue light filters\n- Engage in physical exercise\n\nWhile computers don't directly kill brain cells, moderate and balanced usage is important for overall health and well-being.",
